<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18600507-489">
               <interp inst="t18600507-489" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18600507"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18600507-489" type="date" value="18600507"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18600507-489-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-489-18600507 t18600507-489-offence-1 t18600507-489-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>489. <persName id="def1-489-18600507" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18600507" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18600507" type="age" value="41"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18600507" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-489-18600507" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM WRIGHT</hi> (41)</persName>, was indicted<rs id="t18600507-489-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18600507-489-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18600507-489-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>for unlawfully uttering counterfeit coin.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. POLAND</hi> and <hi rend="smallCaps">ORRIDGE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-667" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-667" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-667" type="surname" value="LAPPIDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-667" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN LAPPIDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of James Lappidge, who keeps the King's Head public-house, in Tooley-street—on 20th April I was in the bar between</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070194"></xptr>
               <p>5 and 6 o'clock—the prisoner came in and asked for half a pint of porter—I served him with it—he gave me a sixpence—I gave him 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. change—I put the sixpence in the till—there was no other sixpence there—the prisoner went out, and in three or four minutes he came back, and asked for a pennyworth of gin—no person had come in between the time of the prisoner going out and coming in again—I served him with the gin, and he gave me another sixpence—I looked at it, and bent it, and told him it was bad—he told me it was not—I then looked at the other sixpence that I had put in the till—I broke it in two pieces, and told him I had taken that from him before—I said, "That you just gave me was a bad one"—he said, "That is a mistake, some one else must have given it you, I have never been here before"—I am quite positive he is the man; I had seen him many times before—he left the house; my husband followed him, and gave him in custody—I gave the coins to my husband, and he gave them to the officer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> I never was in your house before—you bit several more sixpences with your teeth. <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I never touched another one—I have seen you repeatedly before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-668" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-668" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-668" type="surname" value="LAPPIDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-668" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES LAPPIDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am husband of the last witness—on 20th April she gave me a bad sixpence, and two pieces of a sixpence, all bad—I had seen the prisoner come in, and my wife serve him with the beer—I went into the bar-parlour, and my wife called me back—the prisoner had just come in again for some gin—I am quite sure he is the man—I have seen him before—my wife gave me the sixpences, the prisoner left, and I followed him—he joined another man at the corner of Weston-street, and they went into the Hop Pole beer-shop—I spoke to the policeman, and we went in and took him—I gave the sixpences to the constable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-669" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-669" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-669" type="surname" value="BISHOP"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-669" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY BISHOP</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, and live at No. 4, Chapel-court, Norfolk-street, Southwark—I was in the Hop Pole when the policeman came in—the prisoner was there with another man—the prisoner was sitting in a dark box—he and the other man were sitting there drinking together—I saw the policeman take the prisoner away—I saw where he had been sitting, a parcel containing five sixpences, wrapped in separate papers—I gave them to the constable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-670" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-670" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-670" type="surname" value="ENDACOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-670" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ENDACOTT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman A</hi>, 487). On 20th April Mr. Lappidge spoke to me, and took me into the Hop Pole—I went in and took the prisoner in custody—another officer took the other man—they had been sitting, not together, but opposite each other, at the same table, which was not very wide—I took the prisoner away from the table—I did not see the last witness find anything, but he gave me this packet at the police-court—Mr. Lappidge gave me these two sixpences, one whole, and the other broken in two pieces—I found on the prisoner one halfpenny, that was all—I saw the other man searched, and 7<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in copper was found on him—the other policeman is not here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> The other policeman looked under where I was sitting, and said he could see nothing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> The place was very dark, and the coins were in a dark paper—this is it—it was about half-past 6 o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-671" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-671" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-671" type="surname" value="WEBSTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-671" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM WEBSTER</persName>
                  </hi>. These sixpences are all counterfeit—the two uttered are of the dates of 1838 and 1844—of the five sixpences in the packet, here are three of the date of 1838, and they are from the same mould as one of those uttered, and two are of 1844, from the same mould as the other that was uttered.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070195"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> If I had had them in my possession, do you think I should have gone in the other house with them? I went in the house with another man. I was looking to see if I could get any employ. I know nothing at all about the other man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18600507-489-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-489-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-489-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18600507-489-punishment-91" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-489-punishment-91" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-489-punishment-91" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-489-18600507 t18600507-489-punishment-91"></join>Confined Twelve Months</rs>.</hi>
               </p>
